4. Detailed Risk Register (Example Format)
For each risk, include more detail. Example entries below; customize them for Kahana.

R‑01 – Unauthorized access to production via compromised engineer account
Description: An attacker compromises an engineer’s credentials or device and uses them to access production infrastructure or admin tools.

Assets/Processes Affected: Cloud console, CI/CD, Oasis admin tools, production data.

Threats/Vulnerabilities: Phishing, weak device security, lack of MFA on all paths, overly broad access.

Likelihood: Medium

Impact: High (possible data exposure, system changes, downtime).

Risk Rating: High

Existing Controls:

SSO with MFA for core tools.

Role‑based access; limited production access.

Endpoint security and workstation policies.

Logging of admin and cloud access.

Planned Treatment (Mitigate):

Enforce MFA on all privileged access paths and remaining tools.

Tighten role definitions and implement more granular least‑privilege roles.

Implement quarterly access reviews for production/admin roles (P0 gap—not yet conducted).

Owner: Security Lead / DevOps Lead
Target Date: Q2 2026
Status: Open (per SOC2 Gap Analysis)

R‑02 – Data loss or corruption in primary database
Description: Data is accidentally or maliciously deleted or corrupted in the production database (Supabase PostgreSQL). Note: Supabase Free Plan has no backups—gap; Pro Plan provides 7-day retention.

Likelihood: Low

Impact: High

Risk Rating: Medium (P0 if on Free Plan)

Existing Controls: Supabase managed DB; Pro Plan = daily backups, 7-day retention in AWS S3 (us-east-1); Backup & Restoration Policy; DR Plan. Free Plan = none.

Planned Treatment: Upgrade to Supabase Pro if on Free; increase restore test frequency; document runbooks; monitor backup job status.

Follow this pattern for each risk in your list.

